In article <stock.752051842@dutsh7.tudelft.nl> stock@dutsh7.tudelft.nl (Robert Stockmann) writes:
> 
>Well I want to mention here, that acces to Internet cost also a lot
>of money. Here are some prices from NLnet (Dutch service company):
>
[much cost data deleted]

Well, locally, I pay a flat fee of $30/month for a local phone call.  I could
pay higher if I wished, and did not shop around.  8-)

But really, this is all quite beside the point that some people resell
Linux for a profit without mentioning that some of the items included
do NOT work.  If I were to decide to resell Linux, I would make it clear
what worked and I supported, and what did not.  It would be good to still
include those other packages, perhaps, if it included source code so 
someone could play with it.  But of what value is it to include binaries
that do not work other than to make your package sound more complete?
Without some disclaimer, the process does in fact produce disgruntled
customers and in my opinion, is a disservice to all the fine work
people have put into Linux.




