From: ewerlid@frej.teknikum.uu.se (Ove Ewerlid)
Subject: Re: Hardware specs for multi-port serial cards?
Date: 31 Oct 1993 08:52:17 GMT


In article <2avp35$j49@uniwa.uwa.edu.au> oreillym@tartarus.uwa.edu.au (Michael O'Reilly) writes:

   I saw a while back in c.o.l a discussion about multi-port serial
   cards, and some people talking about how you build them.

   Well, based on $US1295 for a 16 port serial card, I want to know how
   to make one. :)

   Anyone got any pointers?? even anything on adapting normal serial
   cards to successfully share an IRQ line?



DFI, Inc. makes a card called MS-400 with four serial ports.
(DFI is a company in Asia.)
The boards I have, have two sockets where a 16550A can be inserted.
Two such cards can be combined to form 8 com ports.
E.g., they support 8 different IO areas.
The problem is that they only support 4 simultaneous interrupts.
E.g., you can jumper IRQ 2,3,4 and 5 to an arbitrary port.

Thus, more than 4 ports with interrupts are impossible.
In my case I could not spare IRQ 4 and 5 so I was stuck with only
2 possible ports.

These bords cost, in Sweden, 450 kronor wich should be equivalent to
something like 50 dollars.

The good news is that the bords can be rebuilt to share the
interrupts. All you need is 4 resistors (1000 Ohm), 8 diodes (1N4148)
and a soldering iron. These passive components can be nicely fitted
on thecircuitboard if the DIP switches use dto jumper the interrupts
are removed. (A soldering iron sucker (is that the right term in
English :-) makes things easier.)

I will not go into details as the actual modifications should be
obvious to anyone that has the competence to even consider this.
The resistor value 1000 Ohm works for me.
The resistor works in a pulldown mode as the IRQ lines on the PC bus
is active high.  The diodes combined with the resistors works as an
and gate.

Oh, the boards have one 9DSUB and one 25DSUB on board and are
delivered with two cables for teh other ports.
(Most larger PC chassis have prepunched holes for additional DSUB
 connectors.)

Don't bother with this unless you know how to operate a soldering
iron and a soldering lug sucker (sp).

