From: dak@rama.informatik.rwth-aachen.de (David Kastrup)
Subject: Re: an observation - SLS flaming results...
Date: 31 Oct 1993 09:41:34 GMT

dimitri@ee.ubc.ca (Dimitrios P. Bouras) writes:


>  So, why can't the SLS people gather all the bug reports/complaints
> off the net and get everything fixed? Seems like the most obvious
> solution to me. Unless they're doing this part time, and it's getting
> far too complicated and time consuming. SLS has potential, I think, it
> just needs a bit of polishing!

Gathering hearsay, the situation seems as follows: those sending Email
with bug reports to Peter McDonald do not get any responses. Even if
bug fixes make it sometime into the release, this is unsatisfactorily.
Beside, release times are pretty stretched out, even where obvious bugs
need to be remedied. This is very much unlike the fast kernel fix
turn around times. If the slow changes were indicating matured stability,
this would not be harmful to Linux' image as much as it is.

Whereas the other releases and their updates as well as the kernel suggest
that Linux is under heavy development, SLS suggests that it is stable
buggy, and no help around.

When Slackware started as a bugfix release of SLS (obviously there was
some need recognized) Peter MacDonald prohibited his installations scripts
to be used and removed the GPL from them.

As to the problems of SLS, two highlights I myself have encountered:
News software is there, but utterly unconfigured, and with no sufficient
amount available to do configuration on your own. If you need to download
the docs separately, you might as well download the whole package.

Net-2 support has a non-standard file layout, so the usual instructions
do not work off the box, and upgrading is effectively made much more
complicated than necessary. However, the installation scripts do not
work properly, at least not for our Class A network here.
