From: ellis@nova.gmi.edu (R. Stewart Ellis)
Subject: Re: Hardware specs for multi-port serial cards?
Date: 31 Oct 93 13:35:47 GMT

oreillym@tartarus.uwa.edu.au (Michael O'Reilly) writes:

>I saw a while back in c.o.l a discussion about multi-port serial
>cards, and some people talking about how you build them.

>Well, based on $US1295 for a 16 port serial card, I want to know how
>to make one. :)

>Anyone got any pointers?? even anything on adapting normal serial
>cards to successfully share an IRQ line?


>Michael.

Dreaming of an 8-line to 8-line loopback test for slap?

You probably already know about the Boca and other clones of the AST 4 port
dumb board that can be accessed with one interrupt(using FAS in the
commercial x86 UNIXes).  That same driver is supposed to work with the HUB6
dumb board that Bell Technologies (later bought by Intel) made a few years
ago.  I believe Boca makes an 8 port board, but I do not know how compatible
it is with the 4 port.  All of these dumb boards need to be updated with
16550 AFN's if they are not already so equipped.  Pricing on the dumb boards
is about $US40-50/port retail.  With two 8 line boards the slap test would
not have to be a loopback.

The price you quote is getting near the bottom of the range for asynch
clusters that work over ethernet.  The Livingston is around $2000 I
believe.  There may be cheaper ones.


