From: cas@muffin.apana.org.au (Craig Sanders)
Subject: tar blocksize on 60MB PC-36 tape drive
Date: Sun, 31 Oct 1993 04:34:46 GMT

I've got a Wangtek EN5099-24 tape drive and PC-36 controller card.

They're now working perfectly with Linux...I had to get the 0.99pl13
kernel because the SLS kernel source doesn't work with qic-36 drives.

what i want to know is what is the optimum block-size to use with tar
when backing up to tape..

The default block-size is abysmally slow.  -b 256 speeds it up a lot!
and -b 1024 seems to be about the same as -b 256.

Has anyone got any recommendations or advice for me?  I want to give it
as much memory as will be useful without wasting it...

does it make a difference whether I am using -z (or -z -z) or not?  should
i use different block sizes depending on whether or not i am compressing?


btw, I notice that although the tar man pages say that tar only works
with compress and not gzip, gzip does work if compress and uncompress
are sym. links to gzip.  Neat!

